<div id="review_1284888549" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1284888549" />
    <a title="Sanjay Gautam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10179929-sanjay-gautam"><img alt="Sanjay Gautam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627894093p2/10179929.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1284888549?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sanjay Gautam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sanjay Gautam" href="/user/show/10179929-sanjay-gautam">Sanjay Gautam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1284888549" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3534887929541832084">It was really a beautiful novel. A story very well written and intricately woven. And it also happens to be a very insightful novel, containing hoards of wisdom.<br/><br/>It just took me around 10 pages to get hooked. It was very gripping, never boring at all. I really liked the way story flowed. It seemed quite realistic. And the one thing that I really liked was that each chapter always ended with an anecdote, which concerned with the happenings of that chapter, but were very insightful in general. Its </span>
  <span id="freeText3534887929541832084" style="display:none">It was really a beautiful novel. A story very well written and intricately woven. And it also happens to be a very insightful novel, containing hoards of wisdom.<br /><br />It just took me around 10 pages to get hooked. It was very gripping, never boring at all. I really liked the way story flowed. It seemed quite realistic. And the one thing that I really liked was that each chapter always ended with an anecdote, which concerned with the happenings of that chapter, but were very insightful in general. Its a story of a man, named Ravi, who happens to be a divorcee and a father of two children, in search of a lady who can be his wife. And in this search he comes into contact with several women, out of which he must choose one to be his wife. That's being the beginning...the story moves on with a gripping narrative with twists and turns(which I do not want to spoil). Actually the main theme of the book deals with subtle nature of choices and their psychological impact. There was one thing that made a strong impression on me was the 'character transformation' of the protagonist, and I was able to connect with him. I also admired the philosophical aspects of this novel but it was the climax of the story that I found to be very inspiring, and in my opinion could not have been better.<br /><br /><br />An Indian novel which I would Recommend highly!<br /><br />My actual rating: 3.75/5.0<br /><br /><i>P.S : I received this book from the author himself in exchange of an honest review. </i></span>
  <a data-text-id="3534887929541832084" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


