    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1265109942" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1265109942" />
    <a title="Abhijeet Shankar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42542051-abhijeet-shankar"><img alt="Abhijeet Shankar" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1434190240p2/42542051.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1265109942?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abhijeet Shankar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abhijeet Shankar" href="/user/show/42542051-abhijeet-shankar">Abhijeet Shankar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1265109942" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10983718990451753158">It is a poignant and emotional tale of Ravi Raj, a divorcee with two fairly grown-up children. <br/><br/>Looking for a soul-mate cum life-partner, to love and to be loved, during the remaining part of his life, with the help of an on-line matrimonial website, the tech-savvy and well-placed executive Raj encounters three similarly-placed single women, also with their children, on the matrimonial portal. The challenges that Raj has are many more than an issueless divorcee. He has to choose such a partner wh</span>
  <span id="freeText10983718990451753158" style="display:none">It is a poignant and emotional tale of Ravi Raj, a divorcee with two fairly grown-up children. <br /><br />Looking for a soul-mate cum life-partner, to love and to be loved, during the remaining part of his life, with the help of an on-line matrimonial website, the tech-savvy and well-placed executive Raj encounters three similarly-placed single women, also with their children, on the matrimonial portal. The challenges that Raj has are many more than an issueless divorcee. He has to choose such a partner who not only cares, shares love with him, but also their children should accept each other. The choice has to be on the basis of ‘yours, mine and ours’. <br /><br />Being in their late thirties or early forties, these employed women have their parents, who are obviously aged, to look after, in addition. The biggest challenge perhaps is that they connect themselves without any external assistance of their parents or elders or even mutual friends. During the process of getting to know each other better, they enter onto each others’ lives sufficiently deep before they realise, which is fraught with possible emotional entanglements, even physical, as it happens between Raj and Dr. Olivia in the novel, before they decide to say ‘ I do.’ All these are brilliantly portrayed in great detail in the novel by the author. <br /><br />Being totally unknown to each other before, there is always an issue of trust, having been bitten once in their traumatic life, they are naturally ‘twice shy’. Notwithstanding that the women are highly educated and accomplished in their careers, in fact, one of them is a doctor by profession in US, they have apprehensions about their as well as their children’s security understandably. Every utterance or action of theirs, however small or insignificant, would naturally go under a scanner in their minds. These thoughts in the mind of Raj form the basis of priceless 'universal laws of life', found at the end of each chapter.<br /> <br />The author appears to have sidelined the story of Priya a bit, who had responded to Raj’s interest on the portal and not dealt in as much detail as he has for the other ‘choices’. As trapped in the 'conspiracies of life', as the author says, Ravi is forced to pursue Dr. Olivia in the latter half of his book, abandoning the chase of other two choices half way, without even meeting them, leaving them ‘high and dry’ as Raj himself confesses at some place. <br /><br />I felt it somewhat strange in the beginning, Olivia, being a M.D. and practicing psychiatrist in the US, pursues with Raj, in what one can describe as ‘love at first sight’ of his picture, believes that he was familiar to her in her ‘previous birth’ and surrenders herself completely to him, in their first meeting in India. But the novelist has the ability to articulate the situation, fictionally, but making us believe its practicality, and the readers really doubt at many stages of reading if it really a fiction!<br /> <br />Another 'strange' thing is (obviously intentional), the author does not reveal much of the past of Raj, as one would have expected the women to know much more about him, as women also have the right to exercise their ‘choice’ as much as Raj has. And this dilemma will be cleared only when you read the 'Finale' of the book, that is when you could make better conclusions, why the author is so conscious about the main protagonist. Those revelations further strengthen your doubts, if the book is really a fiction!<br /><br />It is indeed pathetic to see Raj struggling in his life, balancing work pressure on one hand and life on the other, and at the same time undergoing trauma due to loneliness, and constantly worried about the fact that his daughter is at the threshold of stepping into adolescence when she needs her mother more. Perhaps he might have felt that he would have been wise to stay in his first marriage as life is too short and active married life is further short. After all, what is the guarantee that his next partner would be better?<br /><br />Being a master story-teller that Dr. Hari is, as I experienced in his first book as well, he has cleverly woven the tales of each character in the novel in such a way that the curiosity of the reader to know the next sequence of events is constantly kindled, which essentially makes the novel ‘un-put-down-able’ indeed.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10983718990451753158" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

