  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1268672283" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1268672283" />
    <a title="Nalin Kashyap" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42673884-nalin-kashyap"><img alt="Nalin Kashyap" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430459089p2/42673884.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1268672283?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nalin Kashyap" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nalin Kashyap" href="/user/show/42673884-nalin-kashyap">Nalin Kashyap</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1268672283" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7252640686270524129">I ordered this book on a Sunday morning after reading the review in Indian Express. Amazon delivered the book early morning, very next day, on Monday, and I finished reading it at 1.30 night on Tuesday.<br/><br/>I must admit that the book is so real and truthful about what is happening in the Indian matrimonial websites today. We too had to face many ordeals in our effort to find a suitable match for my own elder brother, who too happened to be a victim of matrimonial deceit and was trapped somewhat in si</span>
  <span id="freeText7252640686270524129" style="display:none">I ordered this book on a Sunday morning after reading the review in Indian Express. Amazon delivered the book early morning, very next day, on Monday, and I finished reading it at 1.30 night on Tuesday.<br /><br />I must admit that the book is so real and truthful about what is happening in the Indian matrimonial websites today. We too had to face many ordeals in our effort to find a suitable match for my own elder brother, who too happened to be a victim of matrimonial deceit and was trapped somewhat in similar situation, though he was issue-less unlike Ravi Raj. Those who after their long miseries, on undergoing pains and trauma of an unhealthy marriage, facing false allegations, separation and legal battle, faced with all their insecurities and the need for emotional comfort from a companion, fall easy prey for all these emotions. But how truthful the emotions and feeling expressed from the other side are, you will never know!<br /><br />I don't think any Indian author has made (in recent time) such a brave and truthful attempt, exposing 'the true life after divorce' and the ‘true issues’, behind what is apparent to the society, of a 'male single parent'. In Indian society it's too rare a case that a man gets the custody of his two children after divorce. When that person is well placed in the society, the society takes it granted that all is well with him and his minor children, unable to grasp the depths of his solitude and forcefully buried yearning for love. When a divorcee gets isolated in society, as not welcomed by other families, it's the children who really suffers, swallowing their pains in silent and misplacing their childhood. A few chapters in the book are so revealing in this aspect that I had to cuddle my daughter so close to me in the first night, when the book was half finished, when I went to sleep. I think, anyone who brood on a choice of marital separation will think 100 times, after reading this book. <br /><br />It's not a book for divorcees, but for the people who stay in marriage, happily or unhappily; for them to understand the real worth of it! (I am not forgetting that the book, probably, was not written with this intent, as it speaks about the hollowness of marriage.)<br /><br />A well woven story, very apt in the present context of fast collapsing marriages and an ever-increasing cases of divorce, all around, in India. Every page of it smells human emotions. It has full of romance, in the second half. It reflects basic human instincts (reminding us that we are just animals). And it has full life. We will find Ravi Raj, the way he thinks and acts in diverse situations, either in some episodes of our own life or in the life of someone who is close to us. It’s so truthful and natural.<br /><br />More than Ravi Raj, it's the women characters, four of them, who really drive the story. Ravi, in fact, is so helplessly caught, without much choices except going with the wind of life. Olivia, though controversial in Indian context, her revelations of childhood abuse and her traumatic experiences in the hands of a Pakistani husband is so shocking and painful. I feel so pity for her, despite her hasty choices in the end. The way America and Pakistan is depicted in the story, you can probably draw a different triangle, though I am unsure if the author brought such underlying intents intentionally.<br /><br />The final chapter, finale and the epilogue are with full of surprises or maybe, you could say they unveil most of the mysteries in the story. The sudden turns in the end really surprised me, making me to read the final chapter and the finale a second time to understand the true senses in it, as they are fully charged with emotions. When you flow with emotions you fail to understand the true sense painted in it! <br /><br />Overall, a very well written, fast read, thrilling story, stitched together with strong yarns of social substances and life theories. <br /><br />(Nalin Kashyap) <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7252640686270524129" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


