    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1266170650" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1266170650" />
    <a title="Padmaraj NN" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42582213-padmaraj-nn"><img alt="Padmaraj NN" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1430545143p2/42582213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1266170650?book_show_action=true">Apr 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Padmaraj NN" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Padmaraj NN" href="/user/show/42582213-padmaraj-nn">Padmaraj NN</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1266170650" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7598332470350850070"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/13851049.Hari_Parameshwar' title='Hari Parameshwar' rel='nofollow noopener'>Dr Hari Parameshwar</a><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25417114.Chase_of_Choices' title='Chase of Choices by Hari Parameshwar' rel='nofollow noopener'>Chase of Choices</a><br/><br/>&quot;Chase of Choices&quot; is an emotional story that facilitates the reader to &apos;experience&apos; exactly the same mental states of the players in the plot, as long as one holds the book in hand. Whatever one may &apos;experiences&apos; in it - craving for love, pangs of a single parent, uncertainties of children, emotional insecurities of divorcees, karmic connections in life etc. etc. - I will not have a second thought, if someone asks me what exactly is the underlying pulse of thi</span>
  <span id="freeText7598332470350850070" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/13851049.Hari_Parameshwar" title="Hari Parameshwar" rel="nofollow noopener">Dr Hari Parameshwar</a><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25417114.Chase_of_Choices" title="Chase of Choices by Hari Parameshwar" rel="nofollow noopener">Chase of Choices</a><br /><br />"Chase of Choices" is an emotional story that facilitates the reader to 'experience' exactly the same mental states of the players in the plot, as long as one holds the book in hand. Whatever one may 'experiences' in it - craving for love, pangs of a single parent, uncertainties of children, emotional insecurities of divorcees, karmic connections in life etc. etc. - I will not have a second thought, if someone asks me what exactly is the underlying pulse of this book, to say 'loneliness'. It's the loneliness within his busy life, as experienced by the main protagonist, that really drives the story. Honestly, it's within all of us, though many of us fail to recognize it, thanks to the complex era of living a busy yet totally imbalanced life. That solitude what we feel even when we are with our family, at work, in the society, among the friends: that pinching feel of truth that we are alone despite standing tall in the middle of the crowd!<br /><br />The book is very exploratory, of life, framed in simple words, and allows one to run his thoughts behind his head, while goes through the twists and turns of the tale. What's mentioned on the book cover - that it's a never ending search - is true. The humans' chase for unconditional love will remain unfulfilled, as long as humans exists on the surface of earth, no doubt. It's not a new theory! But still, a book like Chase of Choices, would remind us about the wheel of life, the never ending process of 'experiencing' the 'experiences', and thus transforming one's personality and attitude towards life, continuelly, with every 'experience'. It highlights the inevitability of change, in every sphere of our own and in others' lives, and how an individual gets changed with every change in his life, without his knowledge. In that sense I would like to call this book a spiritual 'experience' too, if you take the word 'spirituality' in its true meaning! Spirituality in love and romance! Spirituality in one's thoughts and deeds! Spirituality in our worries and concerns! Spirituality in judging and analyzing other's lives! Spirituality in introspection, analyzing our own past objectively!<br /><br />Probably, I can also call this book an 'incomplete' one, as one would feel that incompleteness within, when one turns that last page - as a sense of loss, that the book shouldn't have ended there, captivates the reader!<br /><br />Overall Chase of Choices provides a nice 'experience' that one generally loves to 'experience'. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7598332470350850070" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


