  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1288977255" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1288977255" />
    <a title="Geo George" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43382361-geo-george"><img alt="Geo George" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432527533p2/43382361.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1288977255?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Geo George" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Geo George" href="/user/show/43382361-geo-george">Geo George</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1288977255" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4948070368392785478"><br/>Dr. Hari&apos;s mastery, what I understand, is in exploring the conflicts within individuals - the real divide within us, as two separate entities - the soul and the mind. I am still a fan of his first book as he articulated that inner split so well, in every chapter. I don’t read fiction generally. I picked up this book only because the flickers of some instances narrated in ‘Many Paths’ is still alive in me.<br/> <br/>In this book too, from beginning to end, I could sense that dilemma which every human stare</span>
  <span id="freeText4948070368392785478" style="display:none"><br />Dr. Hari's mastery, what I understand, is in exploring the conflicts within individuals - the real divide within us, as two separate entities - the soul and the mind. I am still a fan of his first book as he articulated that inner split so well, in every chapter. I don’t read fiction generally. I picked up this book only because the flickers of some instances narrated in ‘Many Paths’ is still alive in me.<br /> <br />In this book too, from beginning to end, I could sense that dilemma which every human stares on, when life reveals surprises, murmuring the unexpected scripts in our ears. Though it’s a novel, I think the way wavering of human mind is expressed here, particularly when we are so close to embracing our hard yearned success, how fears (of success, of failure and of unknown) one after other conquer us, causing obstacles getting erected across our path, how our sneaky mind get lured by illusions, tumbling ourselves as preys of allures, and then our untimely repentances when we wake up from our submergence in pleasure… etc. etc. are expressed brilliantly. <br /><br />It’s a fiction! But it’s a non-fiction! <br /><br />The way humans act as animals or as emotional beings or as divine-self, based on our external environments is so true with every one of us, though we never want others to know our ‘animal acts and experience’ which we indulge in secretly, due to our social fears. But the fact is that we are animals! <br />Keeping the story aside, I think we can enter into so many debates on the life philosophies as made obvious throughout this book. As he beautifully narrated in Many Paths, about various options for ‘forgetting and forgiving’, I too think the best option is ‘not to forget’ (our bitter experiences) while you are able to forgive. We need to preserve those experiences, as learnings for future. This book is all about how we handle our own experiences, in making clear our way ahead, while not holding animosity against those who have been harsh to us, in life.<br /> <br />It’s easy for anyone to tell a story, but if you want to show others a way, a path that is fresh and refreshing, you need to have experiences, certainly of pain and suffering. I think the author had them enough, as evident from both his books. <br /><br />I loved it Dr.! Waiting for your next. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4948070368392785478" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


