    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1301064017" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1301064017" />
    <a title="Viju" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22390233-viju"><img alt="Viju" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1455119697p2/22390233.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1301064017?book_show_action=true">Jun 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Viju" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Viju" href="/user/show/22390233-viju">Viju</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22390233-viju?shelf=first-reads">first-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22390233-viju?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22390233-viju?shelf=review-books">review-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22390233-viju?shelf=reviewed-in-2015">reviewed-in-2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1301064017" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16682876619072086564">Firstly, I’d like to thank the author Dr. Hari Parameshwar for sending me a review copy of the book ‘Chase of Choices’.<br/><br/>A lot of life’s decisions do come with choices. Being spoilt for choice is not an infrequent situation for a lot of us fortunate folks. The book ‘Chase of Choices’ deals with those situations where you are in a ‘spot’ and have to make life-changing choices and how making those choices affects the life of the protagonist and the people currently dependent on him. <br/><br/>Chase of Choices</span>
  <span id="freeText16682876619072086564" style="display:none">Firstly, I’d like to thank the author Dr. Hari Parameshwar for sending me a review copy of the book ‘Chase of Choices’.<br /><br />A lot of life’s decisions do come with choices. Being spoilt for choice is not an infrequent situation for a lot of us fortunate folks. The book ‘Chase of Choices’ deals with those situations where you are in a ‘spot’ and have to make life-changing choices and how making those choices affects the life of the protagonist and the people currently dependent on him. <br /><br />Chase of Choices, the author’s debut with fiction writing, is the story of a single dad with two children (who aren’t toddlers anymore) and how he tries to change his life, hopefully for the better, by looking for a mother to his kids, a companion for himself and more. While a lot of the writing appears very biographical, it is not very rare for us to see such occurrences happening to people known to us. The book deals with the anticipation with we approach social media (including matrimony sites, email, Facebook, text messaging) and expect a fairy tale ending with an immediate change to our life. And interestingly as with life, there are some disappointments here as well and that is captured in the form of the story that appears to be written in a straightforward way. <br /><br />A lot of the book deals with the interactions of the protagonist Ravi Raj with four women who appear to be contrastingly different in character and behaviour - composed, aggressive, (almost) desperate, understanding. And we come across these type of people daily in our life, be it at our workplace or among friends. That way, the book surely deals with real characters and it is perhaps one of the biggest strengths of the book. <br /><br />The other strength of the book was how the author has perhaps understood the different types of the human psyche and is able to handle the situations that the protagonist faces with relative calm. There is definitely some maturity and restraint that you see in Ravi Raj in various part of the book and that ensures that the character does not come across a character you cannot relate to. <br /><br />There were a few things that did not work for me in this book. The book, written in a biographical way, need not have sought closure in any form with respect to the characters that the protagonist was interacting with. Many a time in life, we do not know what the people who crossed our lives at some point of time are doing. This insertion of epilogue at the very end of the book made it very ‘filmy’. Perhaps the author could have done without that. On those lines, two of the characters Meenu and Anjali who Raj has a lot of conversation with in the first 100 pages or so seem to be completely ignored in the latter part of the book. Shedding some light on their reaction to what happened to them (in the book) would have definitely helped, rather than just bringing them back in the epilogue with a mention. <br /><br />The book appears to be divided into 46 chapters and the end of every chapter seems to have a post-script note which the author mentions as a nod to the 46 universal laws of human life. While I am sure there are readers who might be able to relate to these and read the book not just as a work of fiction, this was a distraction for me while reading the actual premise. The book does have a few grammatical errors, particularly in the first few chapters, but they do not seem to interfere with the premise or affect the reader’s experience. <br /><br />A book that may be able to strike a chord with audience who are/have been in similar situations in their lives.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16682876619072086564" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


