<div id="review_1296763706" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1296763706" />
    <a title="Hemant Rajput" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8528127-hemant-rajput"><img alt="Hemant Rajput" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359032816p2/8528127.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1296763706?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hemant Rajput" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hemant Rajput" href="/user/show/8528127-hemant-rajput">Hemant Rajput</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1296763706" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer722907013664602501">I received “Chase of Choices” as a giveaway. I have a long list of books to read this year and this book was the latest addition to that long list. Bored with a similar line of books in last two read, I was looking for something new. After reading the synopsis, I liked the theme of the book, so thought of giving it a try.<br/><br/>The protagonist, Ravi Raj, is a single parent. Struggling with the difficulties of raising 2 kids on his own, Ravi decides to give life another chance for the sake of his childr</span>
  <span id="freeText722907013664602501" style="display:none">I received “Chase of Choices” as a giveaway. I have a long list of books to read this year and this book was the latest addition to that long list. Bored with a similar line of books in last two read, I was looking for something new. After reading the synopsis, I liked the theme of the book, so thought of giving it a try.<br /><br />The protagonist, Ravi Raj, is a single parent. Struggling with the difficulties of raising 2 kids on his own, Ravi decides to give life another chance for the sake of his children and started to look for a partner for him and a mother figure to his children. In the online era, he decided to find a suitable partner through an online forum. He shortlisted a few, but ends up with the dilemma of finalizing one. With the guilt of talking to multiple prospects at the same time, he decided to visit them and finalize one. However, destiny had some other plans for him. Olivia, another member of that forum, expresses her interest in him. Baffling with her ideology of founding her soulmate in him and the eagerness, she enters in her life and brings a new twist to his life. <br /><br />The story continues with the evaluation of personalities and attribute of each other to find if they are right for each other. I like the overall theme and the pace of the story, but there are few gaps that make the book an average read. I felt that character was underdeveloped, with a huge gap to fill by the reader’s imagination. The book doesn’t have much vivid description of the characters, surroundings or even the emotional trauma that every single character had. One other thing that I felt created a disconnect was the philosophical thoughts at the end of each chapter. These thoughts are more like a summary of the chapter than having a proper connect with the character and their storyline. An abstract thought requires characters and object to leave a lasting impression. Simply putting them at the end of chapter leave them for open interpretations. While fussing them together in the story brings out the proper essence of that philosophy. <br /><br />Chase of Choice is a good light-time book. I especially like the courage of the author with the ending. Dr. Hari kept it simple and believable, without entertaining the dreamy world end that we expect to every story. Life is full of unexpected turns and twists, some in our favor while other against us. With the theme different from the banal love drama, Chase of choice is an average read for a change and tea time reading.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="722907013664602501" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


